As I close in on 50 and menopause I often reflect on my life as a woman and all of the things I wished I’d known. I don’t have regrets and don’t wish for a do over but I do have a daughter who I want to share wisdom with so I spend time reflecting on the things I’ve learned as a way to make sense of them and formulate some kind of wisdom I can pass on. 

Today was a hard day. The weight of the workload almost broke me. My trauma response has always been “Fawn” and I often suffer for it. 

Today’s reflection: in trying to make everyone happy you will inevitably make yourself unhappy and even sick. There is power in saying no. There is power and self love in setting boundaries. There is power in charting your own path and not giving one fu%k what people think. 

I hope I’m able to inspire my daughter to see her power and harness it. To not spend a life trying to please everyone. 

It’s so hard to teach when you are still a student. But I do find so much joy in it. I also feel the magic my ancestors put in my path to remind me that I am being supported in every way to be brave and use my voice. 

One step at a time. Go forth gently. 
Though good times and bad, when you’re at your lowest and your highest, when you’ve got nothing left and everything to give, you are worthy of love.

Taking time to “draw conclusions” as per the @moonlyapp today. 

Conclusion:

Do not let the patriarchal beauty standards distract you from your true purpose and potential. Our obsession with weight loss, beauty products, diet food and age defying miracle potions is such a major distraction and drain of energy. We could be harnessing our divine gifts and build the life we desire from the inside out. But somehow we’ve been led to believe that if we can achieve outer beauty, defined by an industry designed to service shareholders and the bottom line, we will be accepted, be beautiful, be wanted. True beauty comes from within. We’ve just never been taught that and we haven’t been brainwashed with that value or belief system. Don’t get me wrong, I am a product junkie myself. I’m in an industry that pushes out women because of weight, acne, wrinkles, age, bone structure and skin colour. I’m only beginning to find my true self and as I walk this path I tell myself things like this and sometimes I feel like sharing. I have spent way too much energy in my life and career trying to fit in, trying to please people, trying to look like the prettiest girls who get the roles. I often say I don’t have any regrets BUT it I could tell my younger self anything it would be this: spend time looking inward, the wisdom of the ages is within you, harness it and believe in your power my girl. Believe in YOU no matter what the industry, society, the magazines, the commercials, the casting agents, directors and producers say. You are made just the way you were meant to be made now buckle in and focus on wellness, building your best life and if anyone ever tells you you are not good enough, walk away immediately. 

I know now, that the opposite of Patriarchy is Matriarchy. And the act of returning to matriarchal systems that build strong communities is Rematriation. This is my focus now. Intentionally focusing on returning to balance by practicing matriarchal values and principals wherever possible.

Might take a lifetime but I’m here for it. Who’s with me?

Today is the first National Ribbon Skirt Day. 

For me, wearing a Ribbon Skirt is an act of reclamation. I didn’t grow up with ceremony and I was gifted my first Ribbon Skirt in my 20’s. Our ribbon skirts tell our stories, they represent sisterhood, connection to Mother Earth, to our community and our cultures. They are high fashion and they are also ceremonial. 

We wear them to inspire, raise awareness, educate, reclaim, celebrate and spread Indigenous love and joy while honouring those who came before who couldn’t. 

To honour this special day I’m excited to share some of the stunning photos that will appear in @shinenetworkinc cultural competency project designed for the Canadian screen sector which we will be launching later this year in partnership with @nsicanada 

In October 2022 we brought together 20 Indigenous screen sector professionals from Treaty One to participate in a photoshoot to help illustrate our existence within an industry that knows so little about us and often ignores us. 

These Ribbon Skirt photos are some of my favourite. 

Today, I use this platform to raise awareness. Indigenous people are surviving, and thriving, through colonial violence every day. There’s a reason you didn’t see us, and we didn’t see ourselves on screen until recently. Now, we take our rightful place. 

Shout out to all of these Incredible women who participated. This is only a sliver of what Treaty One has to offer when it comes to the film and television industry. 

To Indigenous representation in front and behind the camera, to more Indigenous owned production companies, broadcast executives and gatekeepers. And to the allies who stand with us and know how to follow and listen. Eternal gratitude to you all.

Hello Treaty 1 oh how I’ve missed you ❤️❤️

Many Indigenous people including my own family many friends and peers, are in a constant state of balancing grieving and achieving. As many of you know, more devastating discoveries were made last week at the Lebret Indian Residential School. Both of my grandparents went there and many other family members from my reserve @muscowpetungsaulteauxnation 

As I began my day, preparing for meetings about a show I’m developing, planning for the Little Bird release and the launch of the first cultural competency course for the screen sector with Manitoba partner @nsicanada I read the news, my inbox was flooded with news about the findings. 

I wanted to grieve that day. I wanted to hide and be angry and give up. It is so hard to keep moving forward with a positive attitude and fixity of purpose when there are so many things pulling you down. 

When I speak about Indigenous representation in the screen sector, when I sound angry and frustrated about the lack and even absence of Indigenous people at the table, keeping the gate and leading, it’s not only because it’s the right thing to do and will change the sector for the better, it’s because we have been deliberately silenced since contact. And it persists, across all sectors. People accept it because we don’t have another way of being and existing. 

My heart is so heavy. Not only because of this recent news, but because of all the things, every day that exist only because of residential school. All of the shitty, devastating realities that Indigenous people are living with as a direct result of Residential school. 

What I want to say here is that some days it’s harder to move forward, to move the needle, to sit at the table, to represent and to strive but most days it is the grieving that fuels my drive. 

For those of you who feel the same, I hope you drop a heart here. Holding space for love, forgiveness and healing. 

For allies out there, please talk about this, ask questions, talk to other non Indigenous friends and colleagues. You may not know it but it makes a difference for the better. 

Sending love to all. ❤️❤️

TW: Holocaust 

Today is Holocaust Remembrance Day

Looking back to the time my sisters, cousin and I joined my grandfather, Joseph Podemski, on a visit to his hometown of Łódź Poland. It was a heartbreaking experience. He took us through the events of the day he walked with his sister to the train station (pictured here) during a massive evacuation of the Łódź Ghetto. He told us there were thousands of women and children screaming as he said goodbye to her knowing he’d never see her again. His fate hung in the balance as he waited for the SS to take him too. Our journey continued with a visit to Chelmno, the extermination camp his mother was taken to. This was the first time he’d been there. My sisters and I prayed and laid tobacco on the remains of what was once the single gas chamber that stood at Chelmno. Our journey took us all over Poland to camps he spent time at and the events that took place and we listened, I filmed, as my Saba (grandfather) relived his experiences so he could pass them all and make sure we never forgot. 

I will always remember. I will always do my best to live in a way that honours his legacy. 

He passed in 2021 and life has been different without him. It’s now my job to pass on the story to my kids and keep his and all of our relatives memory alive. 

#holocaustremembranceday

Yesterday we revealed the trailer and poster for Little Bird! What a journey! 

One of these days I will tell you the story of the vision and execution of the poster. But for now….

The making of Little Bird was a baptism by fire. I’m only now beginning to distance myself from the experience. We were deep in the pandemic. Winnipeg had its worst winter in 100 years. There were floods, ice storms, tic infestations, COVID cases, heartbreak and new obstacles arriving daily. Through all of that, our two warrior directors @ellemaijatailfeathers and @thezoehopkins showed up and led their cast and crew with integrity and grace. Our incredible cast, led by the remarkable @darlacontois showed up every single day and held up this story and its characters with compassion and love. Our crew stepped up during some of the most outrageous challenges and got it done. Our brilliant Production Designer #DavidBrisbin and his entire team of visionaries elevated this story to unbelievable heights; our Directors of Photography @guygodfree and @pinkclaudinesauve were fierce in their commitment to artistry, precision and craft. Every frame in this series is a work of art. From creative and technical to transport and picture vehicles, every single person held this scared story down. It was a dream come true to work with our editors @justinlachance and @maximelauzon88 & sound designer @paul.l.col 
A huge Miigwetch to story advisors & 60’s Scoop survivors  @supacree and @ravey2040 whose lived experience helped breathe life into this story. To my Aunty @sharonanaquod & the whole community of @muscowpetungsaulteauxnation I’m forever grateful for the stories and the attention to detail that you brought to every single element of this story. To the entire Indigenous community in #TreatyOne #Winnipeg #Manitoba who came together to support us #brokenheadojibwaynation and @siouxvalleydakotanation Gratitude to our producer @elle_dee_elle for bringing the light ☀️ and of course my partners in creation @hannahmoscovitch @jeremy_podeswa & @thezoehopkins - list goes on and on and on. When they say it takes a village they were right. I’m grateful to this village forever.

I think I’ve told you about my battle with Lyme Disease and how it took me out for 6 years. I used to travel all over the world for work and when I got sick I couldn’t travel anymore. When I did start travelling again I was extremely anxious about the impact on my body and wellness and I would organize plans so I would have enough time to recover and heal. Basically I’ve been a neurotic mess about it for years. Recently, I’ve started traveling more frequently and for longer distances and as my body becomes stronger it has an easier time recovering. BUT nothing has come close to this trip I just took! I’m writing this to share with you because I’m simply in awe of how everything felt like it was going downhill for me in 2015. I never thought I would heal or get better. But I put my everything into it and this trip from coast to coast - Toronto => Ottawa => Montreal => Halifax => Sydney by car in a white out for 4 hrs => Eskasoni=> Sydney=> Vancouver => Toronto is a first in many years. When people ask me what my definition of success is, THIS is it!!! It wasn’t easy but it was worth it. Through it all listened to From The Ashes by Jesse Thistle and the last couple chapters just got me. Sat on the plane bawling my eyes out. Thinking about how far so many of have come. Through addictions, co dependency, abuse, shame all of it. How so many of us have risen from the ashes and how important it is to tell those stories because those words, that truth pierces through the barriers we put up and reminds us that we are not alone. 

That’s my story time for today. Maybe this week. Maybe next week too.

TW: residential school. Both this post and this podcast deal with extremely sensitive subject matter. 

Listened to this podcast this weekend. I’m a huge fan of @_connie_walker and her powerful journalism and gripping storytelling. With this particular season of @gimletmedia Stolen - Surviving St. Michael’s on @spotify she has unearthed heartbreaking accounts of survivors stories while on a journey to uncover the truth of her own father’s experience at St. Michael’s residential school. This was so painful to listen to but also so important. It’s inspired me to look more deeply into my own history and the impact residential school has had on my family as a way to heal, forgive and move forward in a good way. It has also reminded me why it’s necessary for Indigenous people to have agency in the stories they tell and the way they are told. These lived experiences cannot be interpreted or imagined. I pray for healing, forgiveness and thriving. I also pray for restitution and accountability on behalf of the church, government and all perpetrators of violence towards Indigenous people. Thank you Connie. You are brave and we are so lucky you are leading us in our healing journey.

@jadeharper_kwe appreciation and celebration post. Two years ago she said yes to working with me even though she had never worked in film and television. In 50 days I turn 50 and I’ll tell you, it’s weird. I didn’t think I’d be one of those people who had a hard time with it but yeah, this entire year has had me reevaluating and reflecting like never before. So I’ve decided to combine by love of storytelling with this whole reflecting thing that’s happening. For the next 50 days I will be making a post a day where I will share some of the more interesting events that changed the course of my life. My work these days is looking back at those events and reminding myself of the valuable wisdom gained while letting go of resentments and old baggage that no longer serves me. I really love the meaningful engagement that takes place here so I look forward to your feedback and stories in return! NOTE: these posts are not pre determined. They will come out of chronological order and will be in the moment depending on the day. 

My first post is simple. I’m grateful and exhausted. I just spent two days in Vancouver for work and this time I brought my daughter. My heart is full of so many feelings. There was a time when I was at my lowest, living in Vancouver, abusing myself, feeling hopeless. Being here, working as an actor, working with my baby sister @sarahpodemski and travelling with my daughter is nothing short of miraculous. It could have gone so many ways for me. If you would have told me 25 years ago that I would be here, like this now, I wouldn’t have believed it. It also happens to be the city where my love and I found out I was pregnant with her. So yeah, I’m feeling so many feelings. Gratitude overflowing. 

PS: thank you @wellnessdoctor.ca for the inspiration to post like this

Post #2 - 50 days to 50 

Appreciation post to @rockitdeb and the STAGE 

My first love was the stage. When I was a child, I loved performing. When it came to venues I couldn’t care less. Small stage, big stage, makeshift stage, it didn’t matter. I was just happy to perform. It started around grade 3 when my paternal grandmother took me to see a small community production of Pal Joey. I left that theatre feeling so inspired, I couldn’t stop thinking about the energy in that room. Everyone was so happy and connected. I yearned to be on a stage and feel that feeling all the time, to sing and dance and pretend. I couldn’t think of anything better in life. For the next few years I performed wherever possible. At school we had an amazing music teacher who led the choir. Our class would travel to other schools and sometimes retirement homes. Anywhere with a captive audience. That same teacher saw my raw talent on the recorder and brought me out to perform in front of sold out crowds of elderly people at their care homes across Toronto. My sister @thetamarapodemski and I would sell tickets to shows that we would preform at family events. But the real turning point came when @rockitdeb invited me to join the drama class at her Synagogue Adath Israel in grade 6. Those classes changed the course of my life. During my time there I was a part of two large productions and I pretty much knew by that point that this is what I wanted to do for the rest of my life.

As I reflect on the events, opportunities and people who supported my pursuit of a career in the performing arts I am reminded of the power of a support system. 

Tobacco down for all of those who saw me when I couldn’t see myself. Thank you always to Deb for being my first fan and cheerleader. 

Creative expression saved me. The stage and all of its endless potential to create gave me hope and saved me from drowning in the darkness, shame and fear of everything that was happening at home in my family life. I’m forever grateful for that. 

For the next 50: more performing 🕺🏻

Post 3 - 📸 2007 @_redworks 
The power to choose 

I grew up within a value system built on the principals of hard work, striving and sacrificing want for need. Generally, those values have served me in many ways. But as I got older I felt suffocated by them. Specifically the notion that changing my mind was a sign of indecision and weakness. If I have learned anything in life, it’s that changing your mind can lead to transformation, reinvention and ultimate freedom. The ability to choose is very powerful and the moment I realized that I had agency to make choices, even if the choice was different from what I set out to do previously, I discovered the path to joy and transcendence. 

This practice requires focused awareness and alignment with self and that alone can be extremely challenging to achieve. For me, it was all about shame around quitting. Fear of letting people down and ultimately a lack of faith and trust in myself. But there came a point where (and I quote Anias Nin because it describes it perfectly) “the pain of holding on became greater than the fear of letting go.” Once I let go and made a new choice that aligned with my highest vibration, I found myself in a happier, more grounded, more authentic state of being. 

What I know today that I didn’t know 20 years ago is that there is very little we can control in life. But what we can control are our choices. 20 years ago, heck even 10 years ago, I would punish myself by forcing myself to continue on a path or decision or choice that was harming me only because I believed it was the right thing to do, because it was the principled thing to do and would maintain the status quo.

Moving forward I embrace the privilege and agency I have to make choices. I have seen evidence that going against my intuition and the natural energetic flow of my body, mind and spirit has caused self harm not served me. 

To making more choices that clear pathways to radical self love and joy. 

#50postsbefore50

Post #4 
Surrender and Acceptance 

Been thinking a lot about acceptance and surrendering. I’ve used these words interchangeably, and often rhetorically, forever but I now realize that they are entirely different. I think one is the journey and the practice and the other is the result. In the past, when I would face adversity or find myself in difficult situations I would fall into this narrative that acceptance was the key to moving through darkness and hard things. And you know what, it never worked. Ever. For me, there is no “feeling” or “action” in accepting. It’s an entirely intellectual construct. Spiritual, emotional, energetic transformation is NOT intellectual. It requires the whole self to transmute. So I went within. This happened to take place recently, on the spin bike. I went deep within, searching for a feeling that moved me through and towards letting go and ultimately acceptance. And that’s when I found it. SURRENDER. It’s an active choice that generates a deep feeling. It also engages me with my higher power. Higher self. Higher vibration. Source. Universal intelligence, past and present, ancestral wisdom. This practice of surrendering to those things I have no control over is the way for me. As someone who has existed in fight or flight my whole life, I am practicing the art of surrendering as a pathway towards acceptance of self, the journey, the path and those things I cannot change. 

PS: I used to spin religiously. But when I became sick with Lyme Disease, my body was swollen and I could barely move. I lived with debilitating pain and inflammation for 5 years which disabled me. Post #16 - random things that we have to stop saying

Kindness is one of the greatest virtues in existence. It’s something that every single human being is capable of every single day. This saying is true for many people. But it’s a fact that some of the hardest working people I know are still waiting for the pay off. Equity has a lot to do with this concept actually working. Systemic and structural racism is real and it prevents some people from achieving the “pay off” when it comes to hard work.

3. Practice makes perfect 
Chasing perfection is self harm. Discipline is great. Creating healthy habits is great. Aspiring to be perfect at something is a losing battle. The most important thing about the path we walk is that it is unique and like no one else’s. It’s the YOU in the things you do that makes it special and ultimately makes you shine brightly. 

4.Love is blind 
Love is not blind. Trauma bonds are real and make us do incredibly harmful things to ourselves and the people we love. Love is clear. Love is intentional. Love is unconditional. 

What would you add to the list & why? There are so many more that need to be erased.

She gave me the book Man’s Search for Meaning by Viktor E Frankel and I read it in one sitting. The book became an important part of healing process. I learned so much about myself and my own strength during that trip and it became a transformative time in my life. It planted the seeds of a new chapter. I know how important it was to me that Tina took the time to listen, to show she cared and most of all to help me see my strength. I’m grateful for Tina and I’m so happy she has been in my life ever since. 
When they say “it’s the little things” they, whoever they are, are absolutely right. It IS the little things that can change someone’s day and even someone’s life for the better.

I love sunsets. They steal my heart. They ground me. They are a universal experience that brings people together. They are never the same. Ever. They are probably a lot like sunrises but I wouldn’t really know because, well, I’m not much into them. I love sunsets.

Post #45- The Hitchhikers 

My very first movie. It was grade 9. The year was 1988. We were given an ISP and we could do anything we wanted. By this time I knew I wanted to make movies so I asked the teacher if I could make a horror movie. Not sure why I wanted to make a horror movie but she said yes, so I did. 

I wrote a script, asked a couple of friends to be in it (shout out to @biancaspence) and proceeded to organize all of the elements, secure locations, arrange food and transport etc etc. I asked the Country Style at the corner of my street if they would let me shoot there if I bought donuts and coffee and they said yes!!

I totally forgot about this movie until finding this tonight, but it’s a great reminder of my origins as a producer and director. I don’t know how to watch this thing but if I remember correctly, I think I shot it to edit. I don’t recall actually editing. Which means I started and stopped at every line and switched between actors and shot in chronological order. 🤣🤣🤣 I mean, did I actually do that? 

ANYWAY….it’s nice to be reminded of something I did that planted the seed to what I’m doing today. 

Does anyone know how to transfer this? That would be a good birthday present.

Post #46 - I dream of unity 

I only know what it feels like to be me. In this body, living this life. But I also know that there’s this wonderful intersection where so many of us meet. Regardless of our race, religion, gender, career, skill set. We meet there at that intersection and somehow understand one another. And it’s for this reason why I feel compelled to share things about me and my life whether it be personal or career related. I feel strength at that intersection. I feel energized there. It’s where I find community and belonging. I’ve always dreamed of a world where people could co exist in harmony regardless of their beliefs. Harmony is not one note. It’s many. In order to have harmony there must exist many different sounds. I’ve been thinking and feeling a lot about this lately. I know I’m not alone. I know so many of us, if not all of us, are hard wired for human connection. And it becomes hard and painful when that connection is fractured. Human relationships have been the most challenging part of my life and I’m pretty sure yours too. The second hardest has been my relationship to myself. I don’t know that I will master either in this lifetime but I do know that I will continue to grab every single moment possible where I can meet you at the intersection where we can meet with out judgement and just co exist in our imperfect humanness.

Post #47 - Happy 47 birthday my love

I was recently divorced. It was 2007. I was shooting a thing in Edmonton that involved puppets. Puppeteer, Derek Starlight was in a bind when the second puppeteer didn’t show up so he called in a favour. A rapper he toured with named Plex was available and although he’d never operated a puppet in his life, he was on set within 30 min and saved the day. This was not the man I would have expected would steal my heart, give me children and be eternally annoyed by how wet I get bathroom after washing my face or taking a shower. But that’s how it went. I was not in the mood to fall in love. In fact, I never wanted to fall in love again, ever. But the universe had other plans. This rapper named Plex showed up and within 5 minutes he had a puppet on his arm and was down to collaborate with me. At the time we both smoked so we would take smoke breaks throughout the day and that’s where we locked it down. He was witty, had a razor sharp sense of humour, we riffed off each other, laughed and joked and waxed philosophical. We fell in love. Never married but through good times and bad, through sickness and health we’ve come this far. I saved my 47th post for you my love. On your 47th birthday. I thank the universe and creator (and your parents) that you were born. You are a brilliant artist, you make me laugh and I’m in awe of the incredible odds you overcame and overcome every day to be here with me and our children on this journey. Happy Birthday ❤️

Post #48 - Baby Self 

This is the first photo taken of me. When my parents got me back and decided to keep me and be a family. 

Do you ever look at your baby self and wonder how it would be hold them? This is the shit I think about (no I don’t smoke weed) and then I go down an existential rabbit hole contemplating all of the events and moments leading to this moment and how it all feels like a blip and wonder how we make sense of anything. 

If I could go back and hold my baby self and sing her to sleep I would tell her how much I love her. I would hold her so close, breath in her smell, and kiss her, knowing that she will go through difficult times and despite what people say, one day she will find her voice and she will speak up for herself. And that’s something to be very very proud of. 

I would whisper to her: it’s a scary world out there, there are mean people out there who will hurt you, but one day, my girl, you will stand on your own. You will love and be loved. And that’s all that matters. 

My girl, I’m so proud of you.

Post #50 - Homage to the early work 

Foundational experiences that made a lasting impact 

Consipiracy Of Silence - It was my first real job. It was a silent on camera tole, so I didn’t speak, just cried. I met and worked with @janilauzon and @chocolatewomancollective which elevated my life and inspired me to take the career seriously. This is where CBC casting saw me first and this led to the audition for the Diviners. The story of Helen Betty Osbourne shook me to the core and woke me up to the critical importance of Indigenous representation on TV. 

The Diviners - My first supporting role. I had auditioned for it several times and didn’t get the role. I was 18. I moved to Israel to work on a Kibbutz. 6 months later my agent called and said “You booked the Diviners and you have to be in Winnipeg tomorrow”. I flew on my 19th birthday. I was so so lonely when I was doing this movie until I met @dakotajhouse and we became fast friends and he very platonically would sleep on my couch whenever he was in town because I was so scared and alone. I will love him forever for this. Got to work with Sonia and Tom Jackson and played out scenes that felt like my real life which forced me to deal with my shame. This whole experience was transformative for me. 

Dance Me Outside 
This movie changed my life. I got the audition by accident but that’s a longer story. I could go on and on about why this experience changed my life but I will just say this. I know I most likely would have still been an actor but very possibly not a producer. Dance Me Outside became so iconic that it was the one thing that kept me going during the massive dry spell that took place immediately after the movie came out. Even though I wasn’t working as an actor, I was travelling to Indigenous communities across the US and Canada talking about the film business and how to get involved and it was THAT experience that launched my career as a public speaker and ultimately was the spark that lit the fire to me becoming a producer. 

I wouldn’t be the person I am today without these experiences ❤️❤️

I want to thank all of those who responded to my 50 before 50 posts. I was amazed and inspired by your engagement! Free writing like that every day was therapeutic and really supported me as I closed what was a very difficult and challenging chapter in my life. The only thing I say about 50 so far is that I feel relieved to be out of my 40’s. I have no idea what this chapter has in store but I will continue to focus on living my life in the most authentic way I can. 

Sending you love. ❤️❤️❤️

TW - 60’s Scoop 

I am having all kinds of feelings as we lead up to the premiere week for @littlebird.series 

In 2016 a concept for what became Little Bird was brought to me. I had known about the 60’s Scoop since my early 20’s when I began travelling extensively across Canada and the US working with Indigenous communities and facilitating workshops. I knew about my own brush with Foster Care and being removed from my mother at the hospital (she got be back). I interviewed several survivors in my first TV series The Seventh Generation and yet, once I dove deep into the creation process, I 
was amazed by how little people knew/know about the 60’s Scoop and the devastating impact it had and continues to have on Indigenous families, communities and survivors across Turtle Island. 

This is also the first time I told a story about my own identities. Living at the intersection of being Jewish and Anishinaabe has always made me feel alone. But over the years we made this story, I have come to accept who I am, where I come from, and my purpose here as a storyteller and bridge builder. 

It took 6 years before we were on set shooting. It was truly a labour of love; love for my family, my community, my grandparents and ancestors, my children and grandchildren and every single Indigenous person impacted by colonial violence. The same goes for everyone who made this show. Each one of them made it out of love. It was that love that carried us though what I would consider the most difficult shoot I’ve ever experienced. Aside from the emotional load, we contented with weather and a pandemic that made it feel impossible on a daily basis.

But love. Love pushed us through. And I hope our audience will feel that love. 

Little Bird airs on @cravecanada and @aptnlumi

Story time:

I wanted to share the story about how the opening titles of @littlebird.series came to be. So, originally, we had no intention of creating an opening title sequence but as we began locking scripts my focus shifted to this concept for an opening title sequence. I’m not sure if this happens to all writers and creators but for me, during the creative process, when an idea or character really wants to be seen and heard, they become disruptive and I begin to have intrusive thoughts that spiral into daydreams and often manifest into a real life experience. This is exactly what happened with the opening title sequence. 

I had been visited by an idea. The idea was: what if we could witness the world through Bezhig’s eyes, as a young child, before her apprehension. We could shoot it on 16mm film and make it feel nostalgic. That was the original idea and it grew from there. I could see it so clearly. And then one fateful day, as I was building the inspiration playlist for the editors, I came across a very old song by Buffy St. Marie, called “Hey Little Bird”. It was in that moment that I knew I had to present this idea to the whole team and broadcasters. Everyone was on board so I reached out to @buffystemarie and pitched her the idea. She said YES!! Over the next few months we worked together to reimagine the song and re-record it to time and Buffy really took it to the next level so it felt like spirit speaking to Bezhig. Working with Buffy like that was definitely a highlight of my life. Creatively collaborating with BUFFY …. GEEEZ. Like holy shit. The opening became a massive side project throughout production. From script to post production, it was truly a collaborative experience that included so many artists and producers who were working on she series. It evolved and became what you see here. It’s long for an opening title sequence but I always saw it as an integral part of the storytelling. Drop me a comment below and tell me if you watch or skip.

A story about how the poster (key art) for @littlebird.series came to be:

The vision for this came to me shortly after we chose the hero car. The green one. 

It was so specific. Esther, sitting atop her rental car, looking up, in prayer, in conversation with creation, in a ribbon skirt, on at the top of a hill overlooking Long Pine First Nation. 

I saw the writing of the title. It had to be Patti’s residential school handwriting. My grandmothers. 

I pitched the Art Director at @cravecanada - he went off and created a rendering.

I knew it HAD to be done at @siouxvalleydakotanation so @bennett_podolsky (from picture vehicles) drove me out and we scouted for hours. We finally found the perfect spot.

With the location down, now all we had to do was align the schedule to get everything set up, get Darla there between scenes, make sure the photographer, who flew in from Toronto and drove 3 hrs to Sioux Valley, was set up and ready to go. 

But that day @thezoehopkins location was rained out. It was a big scene for EP 6 and required an epic view. SO I gave up the poster location 😫😫. Zoe and @pinkclaudinesauve loved it. The scout for the poster location continued.

In the end, I found a less ideal place, but the value the new location brought to the series was undeniable. 

The poster didn’t suffer either. 

THEN a wicked ass storm rolls in and we have minutes to get this shot before we get rained out and lose the location for good because the next day we leave Sioux Valley. 

ANYWAY - we got it, it’s exactly how I imagined. The number of people who had to come together to collaborate to make this poster happen is more than most people realize. I love the poster and the story it tells and I wanted to share this little nugget and some BTS of that experience. 

If you’re watching, thank you. Also, let me know what scene stole my poster location? Winner gets a heart emoji. ❤️

In honour of Treaty Recognition Week I want to amplify the spirit and intent of treaties, both numbered and historic, and encourage all Canadians to learn more about the place they live and how broken promises and broken treaties created pathways to success and wealth for all settlers. 

As we imagine a future where we all thrive, one baby step forward would be to understand the original treaties in the place you live and if there isn’t one, then find out why.

Never thought I’d feel this scared of wearing a Chai. Anti semitic violence is everywhere and though no one would ever point me out as Jewish, when they see this necklace, they know. Knowing the extreme persecution and genocide that my family and ancestors have experienced for generations, it feels more important than ever to wear this symbol (LIFE/18) to represent my Jewishness. It’s prompted the most unexpected conversations like never before; it’s made other Jews feel safe telling me how scared they are; it’s felt like a beacon and a symbol of love more than anything else. This symbol and my Jewishness exist beyond war, genocide, politics and opinion. It represents a piece of me, the history and future of my family and the genetic memory in my blood and bones. L’Chaim (To Life)
